.Dd 2026-07-05
.Dt dset_construct 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm dset_construct ,
.Nm dset_destroy
.Nd initialize and destroy a disjoint-set structure
.Sh LIBRARY
IRIS C Library
.Pq Vt ilib_c
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.In dsetuf.h
.Ft void
.Fo dset_construct
.Fa "disjoint_set_t *ds"
.Fa "set_size_t size"
.Fc
.Ft void
.Fo dset_destroy
.Fa "disjoint_set_t *ds"
.Fc
.Bl -tag -width -5n -offset -6n
.It Implementation Macro Requirements (see \fIdsetuf\fR(7)):
.El
.Bl -tag -width 0
.El
.Bl -tag -width 2n
.It \fBdset_construct\fR(), \fBdset_destroy\fR():
DSUF_IMPLEMENTATION
.El
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The functions
.Fn dset_construct
and
.Fn dset_destroy
together initialize, allocate, and prepare, or destroy and free, the
memory of a disjoint-set structure.
.Pq See Xr dsetuf 7 for an overview of the header.
.Pp
.Fa size
specifies the number of elements in the disjoint-set. Each element
initially occupies its own singleton set.
.Bl -tag
.It Fn dset_construct
The
.Fn dset_construct
function initializes the disjoint-set, allocating
.Fa size
elements in each array of the structure.
.Em The arrays are initialized .
If
.Fa size
is 0, the value of the pointers is
.Sy implementation-defined ,
depending on the override of
.Sy DSUF_MALLOC ,
which by default is
.Xr malloc 3
from the Standard C Library.
.Pq See Xr dsetuf 7 No for more info.
.It Fn dset_destroy
The
.Fn dset_destroy
function frees the memory allocated by a prior call to
.Fn dset_construct
and makes the
.Vt disjoint_set_t
object unusable afterward. Every
.Vt disjoint_set_t
initialized with
.Fn dset_construct
must eventually be passed to
.Fn dset_destroy
exactly once; omitting this call leaks memory, and calling it more
than once on the same object is undefined behavior.
.El
.Sh ATTRIBUTES
For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see
.Xr attributes 7 .
.TS
allbox;
lbx lb lb
l l l.
Interface	Attribute	Value
T{
.na
.nh
.Fn dset_construct ,
.Fn dset_destroy
T}	Thread Safety	MT-Unsafe
.TE
.Sh STANDARDS
.Bl -tag -width Ds -compact
.It Fn dset_construct
.It Fn dset_destroy
.El
.D1 St -isoC-99
.Sh NOTES
Neither
.Fn dset_construct
nor
.Fn dset_destroy
validates
.Fa ds
itself; passing a null or otherwise invalid pointer is undefined
behavior.
.Pp
.Fn dset_construct
does not check the return value of
.Sy DSUF_MALLOC .
If allocation fails,
.Fa ds
is left with null
.Va parent
and
.Va size
pointers, and subsequent use of the
.Vt disjoint_set_t
is undefined behavior.
.Sh SEE ALSO
